```python
def image(content, name='Image', mime_type='image/png', extension='png'):
    return extra(content, FORMAT_IMAGE, name, mime_type, extension)
```

One problem with this is that if you don't set `ALLOWED_HOSTS` correctly then you get a 400 response with a body that's just "\<h1>Bad Request (400)\</h1>".  It's hard to work out what you've done wrong without grepping the Django source.  I've raised [this Django ticket](https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/27760) to track making this easier to diagnose.

Even if Django does fix that, I think it's problematic to encourage users to set `ALLOWED_HOSTS` to `['*']`, since this is the kind of change that is easy to make at the start of a project, and then easy to overlook when you come to deploy.

@gawel, can you go into more detail about the existing tests that might fail?

It calls the default constructor, which initializes this object. And there's no other explicitly defined constructor.
```
/**
 * This class implements a socket address.
 *
 */
class SockAddr: public otSockAddr
{
public:
    /**
     * This constructor initializes the object.
     *
     */
    SockAddr(void) { memset(&mAddress, 0, sizeof(mAddress)), mPort = 0, mScopeId = 0; }
```

The `std::forward` below is a nice catch, but this `&&` is not needed here. The `Args` types have been deduced prior to this line, so the `&&` will not have the usual forwarding reference behavior.

```c++
template<class T> 
void foo(T&& x) {} // forwarding reference

template<class T>
struct A {
    static void bar(T&& x) {} // && added to existing type
};

auto value = 1;
foo(value); // fine: T == int& --> foo(int& x)
A<int>::bar(value); // error: T == int --> bar(int&& x) <-- rvalue reference can't bind to lvalue
```

This will break. The Django code for `dest +=` does the following:

```
    def __add__(self, other):
        combined = Media()
        combined._js = self.merge(self._js, other._js)
        combined._css = {
            medium: self.merge(self._css.get(medium, []), other._css.get(medium, []))
            for medium in self._css.keys() | other._css.keys()
        }
        return combined
```

Thus, the `dest` object that was passed to the function is not changed here, while that was the whole point of the `add_media` performance boost.
